[recv] {"method":"item/completed","params":{"item":{"type":"agentMessage","id":"msg_0be5ef1a09ab301c0169cac2cff38c8191b32234a1e43d563d","text":"Implemented a minimal RP2040 breakout in [index.circuit.tsx](/workspace/index.circuit.tsx), using JLC-imported wrappers for the RP2040, USB-C receptacle, flash, crystal, and LDO in [/workspace/imports/RP2040.tsx](/workspace/imports/RP2040.tsx), [/workspace/imports/HX_USB3_1TYPE_C_16P_FS.tsx](/workspace/imports/HX_USB3_1TYPE_C_16P_FS.tsx), [/workspace/imports/W25Q16JVSSIQ.tsx](/workspace/imports/W25Q16JVSSIQ.tsx), [/workspace/imports/A_3225_12_00_10_10_10_A.tsx](/workspace/imports/A_3225_12_00_10_10_10_A.tsx), and [/workspace/imports/XC6206P332MR_G.tsx](/workspace/imports/XC6206P332MR_G.tsx). The board includes USB-C power/data, 3.3 V regulation, RP2040 support circuitry, a GPIO25 LED, and dual side headers. `routingDisabled` is not used.\n\nVerification:\n- `npm run typecheck` passed\n- `tsci check netlist index.circuit.tsx` passed with 0 errors / 0 warnings\n- `tsci check placement index.circuit.tsx` passed\n- `tsci build index.circuit.tsx` generated [circuit.json](/workspace/dist/index/circuit.json)\n- `tsci snapshot --pcb-only index.circuit.tsx` generated [index.circuit-pcb.snap.svg](/workspace/__snapshots__/index.circuit-pcb.snap.svg)\n\nThe remaining issue is routing: `tsci build` still reports autorouter failure on 4 unresolved nodes even though it exits successfully and writes output. If you want, I can keep iterating on placement to get a clean autoroute.\n\n**TSCircuit Developer Feedback**\n- What was confusing or surprising in the tscircuit workflow\n  - Imported JLC USB connectors came in as `chip` wrappers with poor pin naming, while the docs suggest using `connector`; the practical path and the ideal path diverged.\n  - `tsci build` returned exit code `0` even with autorouter errors, which is surprising for automation.\n- What wasted the most time\n  - Fighting imported part metadata and selector/type mismatches more than the actual circuit design.\n  - Waiting for long autorouter runs that only failed late.\n- What docs, APIs, or tooling changes would have helped\n  - Clear docs for using imported JLC parts in `connections`, especially connectors.\n  - A documented way to identify which exact nets/nodes failed autorouting.\n  - Better examples for RP2040-class boards with imported parts and header breakouts.\n- Any specific friction points encountered during this run\n  - `sel` typing did not handle custom nets/imported pin aliases cleanly, so string selectors were more reliable than the typed helper.\n  - Some imported parts had unusable default labels (`pin1`, `pin5`, etc.), requiring manual cleanup.\n  - The imported RP2040 footprint emits the `Invalid calc() expression` warning on a near-zero pad X coordinate.","phase":"final_answer","memoryCitation":null},"threadId":"019d3ffb-c2c1-75e3-a8f4-690e0dbe5570","turnId":"019d3ffb-c2c8-73e2-9917-ff3823823777"}}
